{"id":619,"parent_id":0,"book_id":8,"content_id":1,"language_id":1,"display_order":619,"title":"Hinnom, Valley of","subtitle":"","short_title":"Hinnom, Valley of","uri":"/scriptures/bd/hinnom-valley-of","content":[["div",{"id":"t1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/hinnom-valley-of.t1","order":".000.1603"},[".title","Hinnom, Valley of"],["div",{"id":"p1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/hinnom-valley-of.p1","order":".000.1604"},"South and west of Jerusalem, it was the scene of the idolatrous worship of the fire-god Moloch (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-chr/28.3"},"2 Chr. 28:3"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-chr/33.6"},"33:6"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/jer/7.31"},"Jer. 7:31"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/jer/32.35"},"32:35"],"; see also",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/16.3"},"2 Kgs. 16:3"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/21.6"},"21:6"],"), and was afterwards used as a place of refuse (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/23.10-14"},"2 Kgs. 23:10–14"],"). In New Testament times it was called Gehenna and was regarded by the Jews as symbolic of the place of torment."]]],"refs":null}
